Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: Apache not starting

Solution: Check if port 80 is already in use: sudo netstat -tlnp | grep :80
Restart Apache: sudo systemctl restart apache2
Issue: Permission denied when creating files

Solution: Use sudo for operations in /var/www/html
Verify ownership: ls -la /var/www/html
Issue: Scripts not detecting web shells

Solution: Verify web shells were created: ls -la /var/www/html/testapp
Check script permissions: chmod +x ~/script_name.sh
Test grep patterns manually: grep -E "system" /var/www/html/testapp/*.php
Issue: Logs not showing activity

Solution: Generate test traffic: curl http://localhost/testapp/shell_basic.php?cmd=whoami
Check log location: ls -la /var/log/apache2/
Verify Apache is logging: sudo tail -f /var/log/apache2/access.log
Conclusion
This lab provided hands-on experience with web shell persistence mechanisms and detection techniques. Students learned to identify web shells through file-based analysis, log examination, and behavioral patterns. The detection and removal scripts created in this lab form the foundation for real-world web shell incident response. Understanding these techniques is crucial for maintaining web application security and responding to compromise incidents.

Key takeaways:

Web shells use common PHP functions like system(), exec(), and eval()
Detection requires both file system and log analysis
Automated monitoring provides early warning of compromise
Proper file permissions and .htaccess rules prevent web shell execution
Regular scanning and verification ensure ongoing security
Continue practicing by analyzing different web shell variants and improving detection accuracy.
